t:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n387,\"\"\"OPPORTUNITY COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Opportunity cost\"\" is the value of the next best alternative that is foregone when making a decision. It represents the cost of forgoing the next best option in favor of the chosen course of action. For instance, in the context of Division M, the opportunity cost is the lost contribution of $80 per unit when selling internally instead of externally. Similarly, for Push, the opportunity cost is the foregone sales proceeds of $3,000 when using a telephone system for a contract instead of selling it. Opportunity cost can also refer to the potential revenue from selling unused materials or the scrap value of materials not regularly used. It is a measure of the value of the benefit sacrificed when one course of action is chosen over another, highlighting the importance of considering the potential benefits of rejected alternatives. Lack of scarcity implies zero opportunity cost, as there would be no foregone alternatives.\",8\n2073,\"\"\"RELEVANT COST ANALYSIS FOR SPECIAL ORDER AT PARSER CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Parser Co is considering a one-off contract and needs to determine the relevant costs for pricing the special order. The analysis includes direct wages, supervisor costs, general overheads, machine depreciation, machine overheads, and materials, along with opportunity costs.\"\"\",2\n2074,\"\"\"RELEVANT COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Relevant costing involves identifying and considering only the costs that will be affected by a specific decision, including opportunity costs, to make informed financial decisions.\"\"\",2\n388,\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF OPPORTUNITY COST\"\"\",\"\"\"A company has been invited to tender for a contract to produce a component, R2D2. Production of R2D2 will require 100 hours of processing on Machine X. If Machine X is currently working at full capacity producing 50 units of Product Z an hour, each unit of Product Z makes a contribution of $2. If 100 hours of M